\section{Exercises}

\begin{exercise}
	Consider the sentence ``The CEO of OpenAI, Sam Altman, testified before Congress in 2023.'' Decompose it into KG triples. Identify which elements are entities and which are literals.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
	Given a relational schema with tables: \texttt{Actors(id, name)}, \texttt{Movies(id, title, year)}, \texttt{Casting(actor\_id, movie\_id, role)}. Write SQL for the 2-hop query from Example~\ref{ex:multihop}. Count the number of JOINs required.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
	Explain why KGs operate under the Open World Assumption and why this matters for query answering. Provide a concrete example where OWA yields different behaviour than CWA.
\end{exercise}

% =============================================================================
% Chapter 3: Data Models
% =============================================================================
\chapter{Data Models: RDF vs.\ Labeled Property Graphs}\label{ch:datamodels}

\paragraph{Overview.}
Two dominant data models govern how knowledge graphs are stored and queried: the Resource Description Framework (RDF, a W3C standard) and the Labeled Property Graph (LPG, dominant in industry). Choosing between them depends on whether you prioritise interoperability and reasoning (RDF) or performance and edge properties (LPG). This chapter explains both in depth, contrasts their trade-offs, and introduces the emerging GQL standard.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{RDF: The Resource Description Framework}\label{sec:rdf}

RDF is the W3C-recommended framework for representing graph data on the web. Every fact is a \emph{triple} $\langle s, p, o \rangle$ where the subject $s$ and predicate $p$ are Internationalized Resource Identifiers (IRIs), and the object $o$ is either an IRI or a literal.

\begin{definition}[RDF triple]
	An \emph{RDF triple} is a statement $\langle s, p, o \rangle$ where:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item $s$ (subject) is an IRI or blank node.
		\item $p$ (predicate) is an IRI.
		\item $o$ (object) is an IRI, blank node, or literal.
	\end{itemize}
	The set of all triples forms an RDF graph.
\end{definition}

\begin{example}[RDF triple in Turtle syntax]
	\label{ex:rdf-turtle}
	\begin{lstlisting}[language=XML,numbers=none]
@prefix ex: <http://example.org/> .
ex:Elvis_Presley ex:starred_in ex:Blue_Hawaii .
ex:Blue_Hawaii rdf:type ex:Movie .
ex:Elvis_Presley rdf:type ex:Person .
ex:Blue_Hawaii ex:release_year "1961"^^xsd:integer .
\end{lstlisting}
\end{example}

\subsection{RDF Serialization Formats}

\begin{description}
	\item[Turtle (.ttl)] Compact, human-readable; the most common format for authoring RDF.
	\item[RDF/XML] The original W3C standard; verbose but widely supported.
	\item[JSON-LD] JSON-based, popular in web APIs; supports context documents for compactness.
	\item[N-Triples (.nt)] One triple per line, no abbreviations; ideal for streaming and large dumps.
	\item[TriG] Extends Turtle to support multiple named graphs in one file.
\end{description}

\subsection{RDF-star (RDF*)}

Standard RDF cannot natively make statements \emph{about} statements. RDF-star extends the data model with \emph{reified triples as subjects}:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=XML,numbers=none]
<< ex:Elvis_Presley ex:starred_in ex:Blue_Hawaii >>
    ex:accordingTo ex:IMDb ;
    ex:confidence "0.95"^^xsd:decimal .
\end{lstlisting}

This is critical for: provenance tracking (who said this fact?), confidence scoring (how sure are we?), temporal annotations (when was this true?), and source attribution.

\begin{definition}[RDF-star]
	An \emph{RDF-star triple} allows a triple $\langle s', p', o' \rangle$ itself to appear as the subject or object of another triple. This enables concise reification without the standard quadruple-blowup pattern.
\end{definition}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Labeled Property Graphs}\label{sec:lpg}

The \emph{Labeled Property Graph (LPG)} model, popularised by Neo4j, enriches nodes and edges with key-value properties and type labels.

\begin{definition}[Property graph]
	A \emph{property graph} is a directed, labeled, attributed multigraph $G = (V, E, \ell, P)$ where:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item $V$ is a set of vertices.
		\item $E \subseteq V \times V$ is a set of directed edges.
		\item $\ell: V \cup E \to 2^{\Sigma}$ assigns one or more labels to each vertex and edge.
		\item $P: (V \cup E) \times \mathcal{K} \to \mathcal{V}$ assigns property key-value pairs.
	\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

\begin{example}[Property graph representation]
	\label{ex:lpg}
	Node: \texttt{Elvis\_Presley}
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Labels: {Person, Musician}
		\item Properties: \{name: ``Elvis Presley'', birth\_date: ``1935-01-08''\}
	\end{itemize}
	Node: \texttt{Blue\_Hawaii}
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Labels: {Movie}
		\item Properties: \{title: ``Blue Hawaii'', release\_year: 1961\}
	\end{itemize}
	Edge: \texttt{Elvis\_Presley -[:STARRED\_IN]-> Blue\_Hawaii}
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Properties: \{role: ``Chad Gates''\}
	\end{itemize}
\end{example}

\subsection{Key Advantages of LPG over RDF}

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Properties on edges:} In RDF, adding a property to a relationship (e.g., ``role in a film'') requires reification (creating a new node for the statement). In LPG, edge properties are native.
	\item \textbf{No global IRI requirement:} Nodes can use local identifiers, making LPGs simpler for self-contained applications.
	\item \textbf{Faster traversal:} Native graph storage optimises pointer-chasing, while RDF triple stores often use relational backends.
\end{enumerate}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Detailed Comparison}\label{sec:rdf-vs-lpg}

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\caption{RDF vs.\ LPG: comprehensive comparison}
	\label{tab:rdf-vs-lpg}
	\begin{tabular}{lp{5.5cm}p{5.5cm}}
		\toprule
		Criterion           & RDF                            & LPG                                    \\
		\midrule
		Standardisation     & W3C standard (2004, 2014)      & De facto (Cypher), GQL standard (2024) \\
		Properties on edges & Reification or RDF-star needed & Native                                 \\
		Schema/ontology     & RDFS, OWL (built-in semantics) & Application-level                      \\
		Reasoning           & Built-in RDFS/OWL reasoning    & Manual implementation                  \\
		Query language      & SPARQL (W3C standard)          & Cypher, Gremlin, GQL                   \\
		Interoperability    & Excellent (Linked Data)        & Limited                                \\
		Multi-hop traversal & Triple store dependent         & Fast (native graph)                    \\
		Industry adoption   & Academic, data integration     & Enterprise, OLTP                       \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Query Languages Compared}\label{sec:query-compare}

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\caption{SPARQL vs.\ Cypher: query patterns side by side}
	\label{tab:sparql-cypher}
	\begin{tabular}{lp{6cm}p{6cm}}
		\toprule
		Task                & SPARQL (RDF)                                                            & Cypher (Neo4j)                                                                     \\
		\midrule
		Single-hop retrieve & \texttt{SELECT ?m WHERE \{ ex:E ex:starred\_in ?m \}}                   & \texttt{MATCH (:Person\{n:'E'\})-[:STARRED\_IN]->(m) RETURN m}                     \\
		Two-hop path        & \texttt{SELECT ?x WHERE \{ ex:E ex:starred\_in / ex:directed\_by ?x \}} & \texttt{MATCH (:Person\{n:'E'\})-[:STARRED\_IN]->()-[:DIRECTED\_BY]->(d) RETURN d} \\
		Property filter     & \texttt{FILTER(?year > 1960)}                                           & \texttt{WHERE m.release\_year > 1960}                                              \\
		Variable-length     & \texttt{ex:E (ex:r1|ex:r2)\{1,3\} ?x}                                   & \texttt{MATCH (p)-[:R1|R2*1..3]->(x)}                                              \\
		Shortest path       & Not natively supported                                                  & \texttt{shortestPath( (p1)-[*]-(p2) )}                                             \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{GQL: The New ISO Standard}\label{sec:gql}

GQL (ISO~39075:2024) is the first international standard for property graph querying, unifying concepts from Cypher, PGQL, and SQL/XML. It supports:

\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Graph patterns:} ASCII-art style path matching (similar to Cypher).
	\item \textbf{Composable queries:} Subqueries, recursion, aggregation.
	\item \textbf{Property graph schema:} Labels, properties, and constraints.
	\item \textbf{Interoperability:} Standardised interaction between graph and relational systems.
\end{itemize}

Major vendors (Neo4j, Oracle, Amazon Neptune) are adopting GQL alongside existing query languages. GQL is expected to gradually become the lingua franca of property graph querying.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Exercises}

\begin{exercise}
	Take the triple ``Barack Obama was born in Honolulu, Hawaii on August 4, 1961.'' Express it in (a) Turtle RDF, (b) JSON-LD, and (c) a property graph representation. Identify which aspects of the fact are easier to express in each representation.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
	Explain why RDF-star was necessary. Construct an example of a provenance-aware triple and compare the RDF-star version with the standard reification version (which requires a blank node and 3--4 triples).
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
	Write a SPARQL query that retrieves all actors who starred in movies directed by directors born after 1950. Then write the equivalent Cypher query. Compare the syntax.
\end{exercise}

% =============================================================================
% Chapter 4: Ontologies, Schemas, and Semantics
% =============================================================================
\chapter{Ontologies, Schemas, and Semantics}\label{ch:ontologies}

\paragraph{Overview.}
An ontology gives a knowledge graph its ``knowledge'' --- it defines what kinds of things exist, how they relate, and what inferences are valid. Without an ontology, a KG is just a collection of triples. With one, it becomes a reasoning system capable of answering queries that go beyond explicitly stored facts.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{What Is an Ontology?}\label{sec:ontology-def}

\begin{definition}[Ontology]
	An \emph{ontology} is a formal, explicit specification of a shared conceptualisation (Gruber, 1993). In practical terms, an ontology defines:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item \textbf{Classes:} Categories of entities (Person, Movie, Location).
		\item \textbf{Relations:} Types of relationships between classes (starred\_in, directed\_by).
		\item \textbf{Axioms:} Constraints and logical rules (disjointness, cardinality, transitivity).
		\item \textbf{Individuals:} Concrete instances of classes (Elvis\_Presley is a Person).
	\end{itemize}
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
	The ``shared'' in Gruber's definition is crucial: an ontology represents a \emph{consensus} view of a domain, enabling interoperability between systems that adopt it. This is why W3C standards for ontologies (RDFS, OWL) are designed for the open web.
\end{remark}

\begin{example}[Pizza ontology fragment]
	A classic teaching example:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Class: Pizza, subclass of Food.
		\item Class: Margherita, subclass of Pizza.
		\item Relation: hasTopping, domain Pizza, range Topping.
		\item Axiom: A Pizza must have at least one Topping.
		\item Axiom: Pizza and Dessert are disjoint (nothing can be both).
	\end{itemize}
\end{example}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Ontology Languages}\label{sec:onto-lang}

\subsection{RDFS: RDF Schema}

RDFS provides basic ontological primitives: class hierarchies, property hierarchies, domain and range constraints.

\begin{lstlisting}[language=XML,numbers=none]
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix ex:   <http://example.org/> .

ex:Person rdf:type rdfs:Class .
ex:Movie  rdf:type rdfs:Class .
ex:starred_in rdf:type rdf:Property ;
              rdfs:domain ex:Person ;
              rdfs:range  ex:Movie .
ex:Musician rdfs:subClassOf ex:Person .
\end{lstlisting}

The key inference enabled by this schema: if $(\text{Elvis}, \text{starred\_in}, \text{Blue\_Hawaii})$ then we know:
\begin{itemize}
	\item Elvis is a Person (from domain of starred\_in).
	\item Blue\_Hawaii is a Movie (from range of starred\_in).
\end{itemize}

\subsection{OWL 2: Web Ontology Language}

OWL 2 provides much richer expressivity than RDFS, including:

\begin{description}
	\item[Class axioms:] Disjointness, equivalence, covering axioms.
	\item[Property axioms:] Transitivity, symmetry, functional/inverse-functional, property chains.
	\item[Cardinality restrictions:] ``A Movie must have at least 1 director'' ($\ge 1$).
	\item[Enumeration:] A class defined by listing its members.
	\item[Qualified restrictions:] ``A Pizza must have at least 3 toppings, all Savoury''.
\end{description}

\begin{example}[OWL 2 in Turtle]
	\label{ex:owl}
	\begin{lstlisting}[language=XML,numbers=none]
ex:Person rdf:type owl:Class .
ex:Movie  rdf:type owl:Class .
ex:Person owl:disjointWith ex:Movie .

ex:directed_by rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
               rdfs:domain ex:Movie ;
               rdfs:range  ex:Person .

ex:hasParent rdf:type owl:ObjectProperty ;
             rdfs:domain ex:Person ;
             rdfs:range  ex:Person .

ex:hasAncestor rdf:type owl:TransitiveProperty .
ex:hasParent rdfs:subPropertyOf ex:hasAncestor .
\end{lstlisting}
\end{example}

From these axioms, an OWL reasoner can infer: if $A$ hasParent $B$ and $B$ hasParent $C$, then $A$ hasAncestor $C$.

\subsection{SKOS: Simple Knowledge Organization System}

SKOS is designed for taxonomies, thesauri, and subject heading systems --- less expressive than OWL but simpler:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=XML,numbers=none]
ex:MachineLearning rdf:type skos:Concept .
ex:DeepLearning    rdfs:subClassOf ex:MachineLearning .
ex:MachineLearning skos:prefLabel "Machine learning"@en ;
                   skos:altLabel "ML"@en ;
                   skos:definition "Field of AI..."@en .
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{SHACL: Shapes Constraint Language}

SHACL validates RDF graphs against structural constraints --- like a schema language but focused on validation rather than inference:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=XML,numbers=none]
ex:PersonShape rdf:type sh:NodeShape ;
    sh:targetClass ex:Person ;
    sh:property [
        sh:path ex:birthDate ;
        sh:datatype xsd:date ;
        sh:minCount 1 ;
        sh:maxCount 1
    ] .
\end{lstlisting}

This declares: every Person must have exactly one birthDate, and its value must be an xsd:date. Violations are reported but do not change the data.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{OWL 2 Profiles}\label{sec:owl-profiles}

OWL 2 is undecidable in full. Three profiles trade expressivity for computational tractability:

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\caption{OWL 2 profiles}
	\label{tab:owl-profiles}
	\begin{tabular}{lp{5cm}cc}
		\toprule
		Profile  & Restrictions                                      & Reasoning complexity   & Use case                                 \\
		\midrule
		OWL 2 EL & No universal quantifiers, no cardinality          & $O(n^3)$               & Large biomedical ontologies (SNOMED, GO) \\
		OWL 2 QL & No property axioms, no existentials               & $O(n)$ query answering & Database-backed KGs                      \\
		OWL 2 RL & No disjunction, no existential to new individuals & Polynomial             & Rule-based, scalable                     \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Open World vs.\ Closed World}\label{sec:owa-cwa}

\begin{definition}[Open World Assumption (OWA)]
	Under OWA, a statement that is not in the KG is considered \emph{unknown}, not false. Formally: if $\kg \not\models \phi$, we cannot conclude $\kg \models \neg\phi$.
\end{definition}

\begin{definition}[Closed World Assumption (CWA)]
	Under CWA, a statement not in the database is considered \emph{false}. Formally: if $\kg \not\models \phi$, then $\neg\phi$ holds. This is the standard assumption in relational databases.
\end{definition}

\begin{example}[OWA vs.\ CWA]
	Suppose the KG contains:
	$$(\text{Elvis\_Presley}, \text{born\_in}, \text{Tupelo})$$
	but does \emph{not} contain any triple about Elvis's death date.

	\begin{itemize}
		\item Under OWA: ``Elvis's death date is unknown'' (he may or may not have one).
		\item Under CWA: ``Elvis has no death date'' (false --- he died in 1977).
	\end{itemize}
\end{example}

The OWA is philosophically appropriate for the open web, where absence of information does not imply non-existence. It is also more complex for query answering: a query like ``Who has no birth date?'' cannot be answered definitively under OWA.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Ontology Design Methodology}\label{sec:onto-design}

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Define competency questions.} ``What questions must this ontology answer?'' This frames the scope.
	\item \textbf{Identify key concepts.} Extract nouns from competency questions.
	\item \textbf{Identify relationships.} Extract verbs connecting the concepts.
	\item \textbf{Define class hierarchy.} Use subclass/superclass relationships.
	\item \textbf{Set constraints.} Domain, range, cardinality, disjointness.
	\item \textbf{Add axioms.} Transitive, symmetric properties; property chains.
	\item \textbf{Evaluate.} Test against competency questions using a reasoner.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{example}[Freebase ontology for DCA-Trie]
	In the DCA-Trie project, the Freebase ontology provides:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item Entity types: Person, Location, Organization, Award, Film, Music, etc.
		\item Relations: \texttt{starred\_in} has domain Person and range Movie.
		\item The domain/range declarations serve as ``free'' constraint signals: they are already in the KG and can prune invalid paths without training.
	\end{itemize}
\end{example}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Reasoning and Inference}\label{sec:reasoning}

\begin{definition}[Deductive reasoning in KGs]
	Given a set of explicit triples $T$ and an ontology $\Sigma$, deductive reasoning computes the closure $T^*$ of all triples entailed by $\Sigma$:
	$$T^* = \{ \phi \mid \Sigma \cup T \models \phi \}$$
\end{definition}

\begin{example}[Transitive reasoning]
	If the ontology declares \texttt{located\_in} as transitive:
	$$(\text{Memphis}, \text{located\_in}, \text{Tennessee})$$
	$$(\text{Tennessee}, \text{located\_in}, \text{USA})$$
	An OWL reasoner infers:
	$$(\text{Memphis}, \text{located\_in}, \text{USA})$$
\end{example}

The two main reasoning strategies:
\begin{description}
	\item[Forward chaining (materialisation):] Precompute $T^*$ at load time. Fast querying, expensive updates.
	\item[Backward chaining (query rewriting):] Rewrite queries to include inferred patterns. Slower queries, cheap updates.
\end{description}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Exercises}

\begin{exercise}
	Design a small OWL ontology for a university domain with classes: Person, Student, Professor, Course, Department. Include disjointness axioms, domain/range constraints, and one transitive property.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
	Given the RDFS axioms from Section~\ref{sec:onto-lang}, implement the RDFS entailment rules in Python. Specifically, implement the domain and range inference rules.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
	Explain why OWA leads to non-monotonic behaviour in query answering. Provide a concrete SPARQL query that returns different results under OWA vs.\ CWA.
\end{exercise}

% =============================================================================
% Chapter 5: Knowledge Graph Construction Pipeline
% =============================================================================
\chapter{Knowledge Graph Construction Pipeline}\label{ch:construction}

\paragraph{Overview.}
Building a knowledge graph from raw data is a multi-stage pipeline involving entity extraction, relation extraction, entity linking, fusion, and quality assurance. Modern approaches increasingly leverage LLMs for both extraction and resolution. This chapter covers the full pipeline end-to-end.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Pipeline Architecture}\label{sec:pipeline}

The canonical KG construction pipeline:

\begin{verbatim}
Raw Data --> Entity Extraction --> Relation Extraction
                                      |
                                      v
    Entity Resolution --> Knowledge Fusion --> Quality Assurance --> KG Store
\end{verbatim}

Each stage presents distinct challenges and has seen substantial advances with neural methods.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Source Data Types}\label{sec:sources}

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\caption{Source data types and processing approaches}
	\label{tab:sources}
	\begin{tabular}{lp{4cm}p{4cm}p{3.5cm}}
		\toprule
		Source type                 & Approach                        & Tools                   & Difficulty \\
		\midrule
		Structured (CSV, SQL)       & Direct mapping, R2RML           & Ontop, SPARQL CONSTRUCT & Low        \\
		Semi-structured (JSON, XML) & Path extraction, schema mapping & XSLT, JSON-LD framing   & Medium     \\
		Unstructured (text)         & NER + RE pipeline               & spaCy, REBEL, LLMs      & High       \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Named Entity Recognition (NER)}\label{sec:ner}

\begin{definition}[NER]
	Given a text $D$, identify all spans $\langle s_i, e_i, t_i \rangle$ where positions $s_i$ to $e_i$ in $D$ mention an entity of type $t_i$.
\end{definition}

\begin{example}
	Input: ``Elvis Presley was born in Tupelo, Mississippi.''
	Output:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item \texttt{Elvis Presley} (Person) @ [0:13]
		\item \texttt{Tupelo} (Location) @ [27:33]
		\item \texttt{Mississippi} (Location) @ [35:46]
	\end{itemize}
\end{example}

\subsection{Approaches}

\begin{description}
	\item[Rule-based:] Gazetteers, regular expressions. Fast, precise, low recall.
	\item[CRF-based:] Linear-chain Conditional Random Field over token-level features. Good for well-formed text.
	\item[Neural BERT-based:] Fine-tuned BERT + linear classifier (e.g., spaCy \texttt{en\_core\_web\_trf}). State-of-the-art.
	\item[GLiNER:] Compact NER model that handles arbitrary entity types specified at inference time. Ideal for domain-specific KGs.
	\item[LLM-based:] Prompt GPT/LLaMA with instructions and a schema. Flexible but expensive.
\end{description}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Relation Extraction (RE)}\label{sec:re}

\begin{definition}[RE]
	Given a text $D$ and two entity mentions, determine the relationship (if any) between them.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Approaches}

\paragraph{End-to-end (REBEL).}
REBEL (Babelscape) is a seq2seq model trained on ~200 relation types. Input text, output triples directly:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python,numbers=none]
from transformers import pipeline
triplet_extractor = pipeline("text2text-generation",
    model="Babelscape/rebel-large", tokenizer="Babelscape/rebel-large")

text = "Elvis Presley starred in Blue Hawaii."
triplets = triplet_extractor(text)
# Returns: [("Elvis Presley", "starred in", "Blue Hawaii")]
\end{lstlisting}

\paragraph{LLM-based extraction.}
Modern approaches use structured output schemas with LLMs:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python,numbers=none]
from pydantic import BaseModel
from typing import List

class Triple(BaseModel):
    subject: str
    predicate: str
    obj: str

class ExtractionResult(BaseModel):
    triples: List[Triple]

# Using instructor/outlines for structured generation
# Prompt: "Extract all entity-relation triples from the following text..."
\end{lstlisting}

Key advantage: the LLM can use world knowledge to infer relations even when they are not explicitly stated in the text.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Entity Linking (Disambiguation)}\label{sec:el}

\begin{definition}[Entity linking]
	Given a surface form mention $m$ (e.g., ``Paris''), identify the correct KG entity $e \in \cE$ it refers to, or NIL if none.
\end{definition}

The core challenge is \emph{ambiguity}: ``Paris'' could refer to the French capital, Paris Hilton, or the mythological prince. Context disambiguates.

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\caption{Entity linking approaches}
	\label{tab:el}
	\begin{tabular}{lcc}
		\toprule
		Method            & Approach                                   & Example tools         \\
		\midrule
		String similarity & Edit distance, n-gram overlap              & Fuzzy string matching \\
		Prior-based       & Entity popularity (from Wikipedia links)   & TAGME                 \\
		Neural ED         & BERT-based candidate ranking               & GENRE, REL            \\
		LLM-based         & Prompt LLM with context and candidate list & GPT-4, Claude         \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\begin{definition}[GENRE]
	GENRE (De~Cao et al., 2021) formulates entity linking as autoregressive generation conditioned on the context, using a constrained trie over valid entity names to ensure output is always a valid KG entity.
\end{definition}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Knowledge Fusion and Deduplication}\label{sec:fusion}

Multiple sources may describe the same real-world entity differently. Fusion resolves these conflicts.

\subsection{The Deduplication Pipeline}

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Blocking:} Hash entities into buckets (by name prefix, year, type) --- only compare within buckets.
	\item \textbf{Similarity scoring:} Compare attribute similarity (name, description) and structural similarity (shared neighbours).
	\item \textbf{Clustering:} Run connected components or hierarchical clustering over high-similarity pairs.
	\item \textbf{Merge:} Create canonical entity, link aliases, resolve conflicting attribute values.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{example}
	Source A says (``IBM'', ``hq\_location'', ``Armonk, NY'').
	Source B says (``International Business Machines'', ``headquarters'', ``Armonk, New York'').

	Fusion resolves: both refer to Wikidata Q37156. Merged attributes: \{name: ``IBM'', aliases: \{``International Business Machines''\}, location: ``Armonk, NY''\}.
\end{example}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{End-to-End LLM-Based Construction}\label{sec:llm-construction}

Modern pipelines use LLMs for the entire extraction + linking pipeline:

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Crawl} and download source documents.
	\item \textbf{Chunk} into segments of $\sim$2K--4K tokens.
	\item \textbf{Extract:} For each chunk, prompt an LLM with a Pydantic schema to output triples with entity types.
	\item \textbf{Resolve:} Pass extracted entities through an entity linker (GENRE, Wikidata API) to get KG IDs.
	\item \textbf{Fuse:} Merge duplicate entities and triples.
	\item \textbf{Validate:} Run SHACL validation, check consistency.
	\item \textbf{Load:} Ingest into Neo4j or RDF store.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Tools:} KnowledgeSDK, LangChain, Haystack, LlamaIndex all support this pipeline.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Quality Assurance}\label{sec:qa}

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\caption{KG quality dimensions}
	\label{tab:kg-quality}
	\begin{tabular}{lp{4cm}p{5.5cm}}
		\toprule
		Dimension    & Question                & Method                             \\
		\midrule
		Completeness & Are all facts present?  & Rule mining, link prediction       \\
		Correctness  & Are the facts true?     & Human verification, cross-source   \\
		Consistency  & Logical contradictions? & SHACL/OWL reasoning                \\
		Freshness    & Up-to-date?             & Temporal decay, refresh scheduling \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Exercises}

\begin{exercise}
	Implement a minimal NER system using spaCy on a sample of Wikipedia text. Evaluate precision, recall, and F1 against gold-standard annotations.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
	Build a KG construction pipeline for a small corpus (e.g., 5 Wikipedia articles): extract triples with an LLM, link entities to Wikidata, and load into a local RDF store using rdflib.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
	Explain the blocking technique for entity resolution. Why is it necessary for large-scale deduplication? Implement a simple blocking scheme using the first letter of the entity name.
\end{exercise}

% =============================================================================
% Chapter 6: Querying Knowledge Graphs
% =============================================================================
\chapter{Querying Knowledge Graphs}\label{ch:querying}

\paragraph{Overview.}
A knowledge graph is only as useful as our ability to query it. This chapter covers the two dominant query languages --- SPARQL (for RDF) and Cypher (for property graphs) --- along with query optimisation techniques and the emerging GQL standard.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{SPARQL}\label{sec:sparql}

SPARQL (SPARQL Protocol and RDF Query Language) is the W3C standard for querying RDF data. Its syntax resembles SQL, but operates on graph patterns instead of tables.

\subsection{Basic Graph Pattern Matching}

\begin{lstlisting}[language=SQL,numbers=none]
PREFIX ex: <http://example.org/>
SELECT ?movie ?year
WHERE {
  ex:Elvis_Presley ex:starred_in ?movie .
  ?movie ex:release_year ?year .
  FILTER(?year > 1960)
}
\end{lstlisting}

The WHERE clause defines a \emph{basic graph pattern (BGP)} --- a set of triple patterns that must match simultaneously. SPARQL evaluates the BGP by finding all variable bindings that satisfy all triple patterns.

\subsection{SPARQL Query Forms}

\begin{table}[h]
	\centering
	\caption{SPARQL query forms}
	\label{tab:sparql-forms}
	\begin{tabular}{lp{4cm}p{5cm}}
		\toprule
		Form      & Returns                    & Example                              \\
		\midrule
		SELECT    & Table of variable bindings & ``Find all movies Elvis starred in'' \\
		CONSTRUCT & RDF graph                  & ``Create co-star relationships''     \\
		ASK       & Boolean                    & ``Did Elvis work with Tom Jones?''   \\
		DESCRIBE  & RDF graph                  & ``Get all facts about Elvis''        \\
		\bottomrule
	\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Property Paths (Multi-hop)}

SPARQL 1.1 introduced regular expression paths for multi-hop traversal:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=SQL,numbers=none]
# Two-hop: Elvis -> movie -> director
SELECT ?director WHERE {
  ex:Elvis_Presley ex:starred_in / ex:directed_by ?director
}

# Variable length: 1 to 3 hops
SELECT ?x WHERE {
  ex:Elvis_Presley (ex:starred_in|ex:produced_by){1,3} ?x
}

# Arbitrary length (Kleene star)
SELECT ?x WHERE {
  ex:Elvis_Presley ex:influenced* ?x
}
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{CONSTRUCT Queries}

CONSTRUCT creates new RDF triples from query results, enabling inference at query time:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=SQL,numbers=none]
CONSTRUCT { ?s ex:worked_with ?o }
WHERE {
  ?s ex:starred_in ?m .
  ?o ex:starred_in ?m .
  FILTER(?s != ?o)
}
\end{lstlisting}

This materialises co-star relationships without storing them explicitly.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Cypher}\label{sec:cypher}

Cypher is Neo4j's property graph query language, using ASCII-art pattern syntax:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=SQL,numbers=none]
// Find Elvis's movies
MATCH (p:Person {name: 'Elvis Presley'})-[:STARRED_IN]->(m:Movie)
RETURN m.title, m.release_year

// Two-hop with condition
MATCH (p:Person {name: 'Elvis Presley'})-[:STARRED_IN]->()
      -[:DIRECTED_BY]->(d:Person)
WHERE d.birth_year > 1930
RETURN d.name

// Variable-length path
MATCH path = (p:Person {name: 'Elvis Presley'})
             -[:STARRED_IN|PRODUCED_BY*1..3]->(x)
RETURN x.name, length(path) AS hops
\end{lstlisting}

\subsection{Shortest Path}

Cypher has native shortest-path support, which SPARQL lacks:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=SQL,numbers=none]
MATCH path = shortestPath(
  (p1:Person {name: 'Elvis Presley'})-[*]-
  (p2:Person {name: 'Tom Jones'})
)
RETURN path
\end{lstlisting}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Query Optimisation}\label{sec:query-opt}

\subsection{General Principles}

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Filter early:} Push WHERE conditions as deep as possible into the query plan.
	\item \textbf{Index frequent patterns:} Entity labels, property equality, commonly joined relations.
	\item \textbf{Limit intermediate results:} Use LIMIT for exploratory queries.
	\item \textbf{Avoid Cartesian products:} Every disconnected MATCH/pattern multiplies the result set.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Join Ordering}

The query optimiser's most critical decision is join order. For SPARQL:
$$P(x,y) \bowtie Q(y,z) \bowtie R(z,w)$$
Different orderings can differ in execution time by orders of magnitude. Modern optimisers use cardinality estimates from statistical summaries of the KG.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Exercises}

\begin{exercise}
	Given a KG with schema: Person, Movie, starred\_in, directed\_by, produced\_by, release\_year, birth\_year. Write SPARQL queries for:
	\begin{enumerate}
		\item All movies directed by directors born after 1950 featuring actors who also starred in a Scorsese film.
		\item The shortest path between two actors who have never co-starred.
	\end{enumerate}
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
	Write the equivalent Cypher queries. Which aspects are easier in each language?
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
Explain how a SPARQL query optimizer would evaluate the query from (1a). What join orders are possible? Which is likely optimal and why?
\end{exercise}

% =============================================================================
% Chapter 7: Knowledge Graph Embeddings
% =============================================================================
\chapter{Knowledge Graph Embeddings}\label{ch:embeddings}

\paragraph{Overview.}
KGs are symbolic and discrete. Machine learning needs continuous representations. KG embeddings map entities and relations to vectors in $\R^d$ such that the KG's structural patterns are preserved as geometric relationships. This chapter develops the main families of embedding models, their training objectives, and their limitations.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{The Embedding Problem}\label{sec:emb-problem}

\begin{definition}[KG embedding]
Given a knowledge graph $\kg = (\cE, \cR, T)$, a \emph{knowledge graph embedding} is a mapping:
$$\phi: \cE \to \R^d, \quad \psi: \cR \to \R^d$$
such that for each triple $(h, r, t) \in T$, a scoring function $f: \cE \times \cR \times \cE \to \R$ satisfies:
$$f(\phi(h), \psi(r), \phi(t)) \gg f(\phi(h'), \psi(r), \phi(t'))$$
for randomly corrupted triples $(h', r, t') \notin T$.
\end{definition}

The scoring function $f$ is chosen to reflect a geometric intuition about how relations transform entity vectors.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Translational Models}\label{sec:translational}

\subsection{TransE (Bordes et al., 2013)}

The simplest and most influential embedding model. The intuition: for a true triple $(h, r, t)$, the head entity embedding plus the relation embedding should approximate the tail entity embedding.

\begin{definition}[TransE scoring]
$$f(h, r, t) = -\|\mathbf{h} + \mathbf{r} - \mathbf{t}\|_p$$
where $\|\cdot\|_p$ is the $L_1$ or $L_2$ norm. Higher scores indicate more plausible triples.
\end{definition}

\begin{example}[TransE geometric intuition]
If we learn embeddings such that:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{h}_{\text{Elvis}} + \mathbf{r}_{\text{starred\_in}} &\approx \mathbf{t}_{\text{Blue\_Hawaii}} \\
\mathbf{h}_{\text{Elvis}} + \mathbf{r}_{\text{starred\_in}} &\approx \mathbf{t}_{\text{Jailhouse\_Rock}}
\end{align*}
then $\mathbf{t}_{\text{Blue\_Hawaii}}$ and $\mathbf{t}_{\text{Jailhouse\_Rock}}$ should be close in vector space, reflecting that both are Elvis movies.
\end{example}

\begin{proposition}[Limitations of TransE]
TransE cannot model:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Symmetric relations:} If $(h, r, t)$ and $(t, r, h)$ both hold (e.g., \texttt{spouse\_of}), TransE requires $\mathbf{r} = 0$ and $\mathbf{h} \approx \mathbf{t}$, collapsing the representation.
  \item \textbf{1-to-N relations:} If $(h, r, t_1)$ and $(h, r, t_2)$ both hold, TransE forces $\mathbf{t}_1 \approx \mathbf{t}_2$.
  \item \textbf{Composition:} Cannot represent $r_1 \circ r_2 = r_3$ (e.g., mother\_of $\circ$ parent\_of = grandmother\_of).
\end{itemize}
\end{proposition}

\subsection{RotatE (Sun et al., 2019)}

RotatE addresses TransE's limitations by embedding in complex space, with relations as rotations.

\begin{definition}[RotatE scoring]
Embeddings are in $\C^d$ (i.e., $d$-dimensional complex vectors). For each triple:
$$\mathbf{t} = \mathbf{h} \circ \mathbf{r} \quad \text{(element-wise Hadamard product)}$$
where $|\mathbf{r}_i| = 1$ for all $i$ (each component of $\mathbf{r}$ lies on the unit circle). The score is:
$$f(h, r, t) = -\|\mathbf{h} \circ \mathbf{r} - \mathbf{t}\|$$
\end{definition}

\begin{theorem}[RotatE expressivity]
\label{thm:rotate}
RotatE can model all four relational patterns simultaneously:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Symmetry:} $\mathbf{r}_i = \pm 1$ for all $i$
  \item \textbf{Antisymmetry:} $\mathbf{r}_i \neq \pm 1$
  \item \textbf{Inversion:} $\mathbf{r}_2 = \overline{\mathbf{r}}_1$ (complex conjugate)
  \item \textbf{Composition:} $\mathbf{r}_3 = \mathbf{r}_1 \circ \mathbf{r}_2$
\end{itemize}
\end{theorem}

\noindent This makes RotatE strictly more expressive than TransE, DistMult, and Compl\'{e}x.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Bilinear Models}\label{sec:bilinear}

\subsection{DistMult (Yang et al., 2015)}

\begin{definition}[DistMult scoring]
$$f(h, r, t) = \mathbf{h}^\top \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{r}) \, \mathbf{t} = \sum_{i=1}^d h_i \cdot r_i \cdot t_i$$
\end{definition}

DistMult is simple and efficient ($O(d)$ per triple), but $f(h, r, t) = f(t, r, h)$, so it can only model symmetric relations.

\subsection{ComplEx (Trouillon et al., 2016)}

ComplEx extends DistMult to complex space, using the complex conjugate to break symmetry:

\begin{definition}[ComplEx scoring]
$$f(h, r, t) = \operatorname{Re}(\mathbf{h}^\top \operatorname{diag}(\mathbf{r}) \, \overline{\mathbf{t}}) = \langle \operatorname{Re}(\mathbf{h}), \operatorname{Re}(\mathbf{r}), \operatorname{Re}(\mathbf{t}) \rangle + \langle \operatorname{Im}(\mathbf{h}), \operatorname{Re}(\mathbf{r}), \operatorname{Im}(\mathbf{t}) \rangle + \langle \operatorname{Re}(\mathbf{h}), \operatorname{Im}(\mathbf{r}), \operatorname{Im}(\mathbf{t}) \rangle - \langle \operatorname{Im}(\mathbf{h}), \operatorname{Im}(\mathbf{r}), \operatorname{Re}(\mathbf{t}) \rangle$$
\end{definition}

The asymmetry comes from the conjugate operation: $f(h, r, t) \neq f(t, r, h)$ in general, enabling modelling of antisymmetric relations while retaining DistMult's efficiency.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Training KG Embeddings}\label{sec:emb-training}

\subsection{Loss Functions}

Given a set of true triples $\mathcal{D}^+$ and corrupted triples $\mathcal{D}^-$, the standard training objective is:

\begin{definition}[Margin ranking loss]
$$\mathcal{L} = \sum_{(h,r,t) \in \mathcal{D}^+} \sum_{(h',r,t') \in \mathcal{D}^-} \max(0, \gamma + f(h', r, t') - f(h, r, t))$$
where $\gamma > 0$ is a margin hyperparameter.
\end{definition}

Alternative losses: binary cross-entropy (DistMult), negative log-likelihood (ComplEx), self-adversarial sampling (RotatE).

\subsection{Negative Sampling}

For each true triple, we corrupt either the head or tail:

\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python,numbers=none]
def corrupt_triple(h, r, t, num_entities):
    if random.random() < 0.5:
        h_corrupt = random.randint(0, num_entities - 1)
        return (h_corrupt, r, t)
    else:
        t_corrupt = random.randint(0, num_entities - 1)
        return (h, r, t_corrupt)
\end{lstlisting}

Key insight: uniform negative sampling (choose random entity) is simple but produces easy negatives. Self-adversarial sampling (RotatE) weights negative samples by their current score, focusing on harder cases.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Evaluation Protocol}\label{sec:emb-eval}

For link prediction (predicting missing $(h, r, ?)$ or $(?, r, t)$):

\begin{enumerate}
  \item For each test triple $(h, r, t)$, replace $t$ with every entity $e \in \cE$.
  \item Score all $|\cE|$ candidates.
  \item Compute the rank of the true entity $t$.
  \item Apply \emph{filtered} setting: remove any corrupted triple that exists in the training/validation/test set.
  \item Aggregate ranks into MRR and Hits@K.
\end{enumerate}

\begin{definition}[Evaluation metrics]
\begin{align*}
\text{MRR} &= \frac{1}{|\mathcal{D}_{\text{test}}|} \sum_{t \in \mathcal{D}_{\text{test}}} \frac{1}{\text{rank}(t)} \\
\text{Hits@K} &= \frac{1}{|\mathcal{D}_{\text{test}}|} \sum_{t \in \mathcal{D}_{\text{test}}} \bone_{\text{rank}(t) \le K}
\end{align*}
\end{definition}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Model comparison on FB15k-237 (filtered)}
\label{tab:emb-compare}
\begin{tabular}{lccc}
\toprule
Model & MRR & Hits@1 & Hits@10 \\
\midrule
TransE & 0.294 & -- & 0.465 \\
DistMult & 0.241 & 0.155 & 0.419 \\
ComplEx & 0.278 & 0.194 & 0.450 \\
RotatE & 0.338 & 0.241 & 0.533 \\
TuckER & 0.358 & 0.266 & 0.544 \\
NBFNet (GNN) & 0.417 & 0.321 & 0.582 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Exercises}

\begin{exercise}
Show algebraically why TransE cannot model symmetric relations. Prove that if $(h, r, t)$ and $(t, r, h)$ are both true, TransE forces $\mathbf{r} = 0$ and $\mathbf{h} \approx \mathbf{t}$.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
Implement the scoring function for DistMult and RotatE in PyTorch. Compare the number of parameters each model requires for $|\cE| = 10{,}000$, $|\cR| = 100$, $d = 200$.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
Explain the ``filtered setting'' for KG embedding evaluation. Why is it necessary? What happens if we do not filter out corrupted triples that exist in the training set?
\end{exercise}

% =============================================================================
% Chapter 8: Graph Neural Networks for KGs
% =============================================================================
\chapter{Graph Neural Networks for KGs}\label{ch:gnns}

\paragraph{Overview.}
Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) learn node representations via iterative message passing between neighbours. For KGs, GNNs offer context-dependent representations (the same entity gets different embeddings for different query relations) and inductive capabilities (handling unseen entities). This chapter covers the main GNN architectures, their application to KGs, and the theoretical limits of their expressivity.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{The Message-Passing Paradigm}\label{sec:mpnn}

\begin{definition}[Message-passing GNN]
Let $G = (V, E)$ be a graph with node features $\mathbf{x}_v \in \R^{d_0}$. A message-passing GNN computes representations through $L$ layers:
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{m}_v^{(l)} &= \operatorname{AGG}^{(l)}\!\left( \left\{ \phi^{(l)}(\mathbf{h}_u^{(l-1)}, \mathbf{h}_v^{(l-1)}, \mathbf{e}_{uv}) : u \in \mathcal{N}(v) \right\} \right) \\
\mathbf{h}_v^{(l)} &= \operatorname{UPDATE}^{(l)}(\mathbf{h}_v^{(l-1)}, \mathbf{m}_v^{(l)})
\end{align*}
where $\mathbf{h}_v^{(0)} = \mathbf{x}_v$, $\mathcal{N}(v)$ is the neighbourhood of $v$, and $\mathbf{e}_{uv}$ are optional edge features.
\end{definition}

\noindent\textbf{Analogy:} A GNN is a dinner party. Each person (node) talks to their neighbours, aggregates what they hear (AGG), and updates their own understanding (UPDATE). After $L$ rounds, everyone has a view of the conversation within their $L$-hop radius.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Key Architectures}\label{sec:gnn-archs}

\subsection{Graph Convolutional Network (GCN)}

GCN (Kipf \& Welling, 2017) uses mean-pooling with symmetric normalisation:

\begin{definition}[GCN layer]
$$\mathbf{h}_v^{(l)} = \sigma\!\left( \mathbf{W}^{(l)} \sum_{u \in \mathcal{N}(v) \cup \{v\}} \frac{1}{\sqrt{\deg(u)\deg(v)}} \mathbf{h}_u^{(l-1)} \right)$$
\end{definition}

The normalisation factor $\frac{1}{\sqrt{\deg(u)\deg(v)}}$ prevents degree-biased representations and stabilises training.

\subsection{Graph Attention Network (GAT)}

GAT (Veli\v{c}kovi\'{c} et al., 2018) learns attention weights for each neighbour:

\begin{definition}[GAT layer]
$$\mathbf{h}_v^{(l)} = \sigma\!\left( \sum_{u \in \mathcal{N}(v) \cup \{v\}} \alpha_{vu} \mathbf{W}^{(l)} \mathbf{h}_u^{(l-1)} \right)$$
where attention coefficients are:
$$\alpha_{vu} = \frac{\exp(\mathbf{a}^\top [\mathbf{W}\mathbf{h}_v \| \mathbf{W}\mathbf{h}_u])}{\sum_{w \in \mathcal{N}(v)} \exp(\mathbf{a}^\top [\mathbf{W}\mathbf{h}_v \| \mathbf{W}\mathbf{h}_w])}$$
and $\|$ denotes concatenation.
\end{definition}

Multi-head attention (concatenating/averaging $K$ independent attention heads) improves stability.

\subsection{GraphSAGE (Hamilton et al., 2017)}

GraphSAGE introduced \emph{inductive} learning --- generalising to unseen nodes at inference:

\begin{definition}[GraphSAGE layer]
$$\mathbf{h}_v^{(l)} = \sigma\!\left( \mathbf{W}^{(l)} \cdot \left[ \mathbf{h}_v^{(l-1)} \middle\| \operatorname{AGG}^{(l)}\!\left( \left\{ \mathbf{h}_u^{(l-1)} : u \in \mathcal{N}(v) \right\} \right) \right] \right)$$
where AGG can be mean, LSTM, or max-pooling over neighbours.
\end{definition}

\subsection{Relational Graph Convolution (R-GCN)}

For KGs with multiple relation types, R-GCN uses relation-specific transformations:

\begin{definition}[R-GCN layer]
$$\mathbf{h}_v^{(l)} = \sigma\!\left( \mathbf{W}_0^{(l)} \mathbf{h}_v^{(l-1)} + \sum_{r \in \cR} \sum_{u \in \mathcal{N}_r(v)} \frac{1}{c_{v,r}} \mathbf{W}_r^{(l)} \mathbf{h}_u^{(l-1)} \right)$$
where $\mathcal{N}_r(v)$ are neighbours connected by relation $r$, and $c_{v,r}$ is a normalisation constant.
\end{definition}

\begin{remark}
R-GCN's per-relation weight matrices $\mathbf{W}_r$ lead to $O(|\cR| \cdot d^2)$ parameters. For KGs with thousands of relations, this becomes prohibitive. Basis decomposition and block-diagonal matrices reduce the parameter count.
\end{remark}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{GNNs for Link Prediction}\label{sec:gnn-lp}

\subsection{NBFNet (Zhu et al., 2021)}

NBFNet formulates link prediction as label propagation: given a query $(h, r, ?)$, run a GNN with the head entity as the source of a ``query signal''.

\begin{algorithm}[h]
\caption{NBFNet forward pass for link prediction}
\label{alg:nbfnet}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=Python,numbers=none]
def nbfnet_link_predict(kg, h, r, num_layers):
    # Initialise: h gets score 1, all others 0
    scores = {e: 0 for e in kg.entities}
    scores[h] = 1.0

    for layer in range(num_layers):
        new_scores = {}
        for e in kg.entities:
            # Message from incoming neighbours
            msg = 0
            for (rel, source) in kg.in_edges(e):
                msg += W_rel * scores[source]
            new_scores[e] = UPDATE(scores[e], msg)
        scores = new_scores

    return scores
\end{lstlisting}
\end{algorithm}

Key insight: unlike TransE (which stores a single vector per entity), NBFNet computes representations \emph{contextually} --- the same entity gets different representations for different query relations.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Expressivity Limits}\label{sec:gnn-express}

\begin{theorem}[1-WL equivalence]
Message-passing GNNs are at most as powerful as the 1-WL graph isomorphism test (Xu et al., 2019; Morris et al., 2019). Specifically:
\begin{itemize}
  \item GCN, GAT, GraphSAGE are strictly less powerful than 1-WL.
  \item GIN (with sum aggregation and MLP update) matches 1-WL.
  \item No MP-GNN can distinguish regular graphs of the same degree.
\end{itemize}
\end{theorem}

\begin{corollary}
For link prediction in KGs, MP-GNNs cannot distinguish non-isomorphic neighbourhood structures that share the same multiset of node features. This motivates structural features (positional encodings, random walk features) as additional inputs.
\end{corollary}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Exercises}

\begin{exercise}
Implement a single GCN layer in PyTorch. Verify that the normalisation factor $\frac{1}{\sqrt{\deg(u)\deg(v)}}$ prevents representation collapse for high-degree nodes.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
Compare the parameter count of GCN, GAT (with $K$ heads), and R-GCN for $d = 256$, $|\cR| = 50$, $K = 4$.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
Explain why GIN's sum aggregation is more powerful than mean or max aggregation. Provide a counterexample where mean aggregation fails to distinguish two non-isomorphic graphs.
\end{exercise}

% =============================================================================
% Chapter 9: Knowledge Graphs and LLMs: GraphRAG
% =============================================================================
\chapter{Knowledge Graphs and LLMs: GraphRAG}\label{ch:graphrag}

\paragraph{Overview.}
Large Language Models (LLMs) have revolutionised NLP but suffer from hallucinations, staleness, and lack of structured reasoning. Knowledge graphs provide precise, structured, grounded facts. GraphRAG --- the integration of KGs with LLM-based retrieval-augmented generation --- combines the strengths of both paradigms. This chapter surveys the GraphRAG landscape, from basic retrieval to constrained decoding.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{The Limits of Standard RAG}\label{sec:rag-limits}

Standard Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) retrieves text chunks via vector similarity:

\begin{verbatim}
Query --> Embed --> Vector Search --> Top-k Chunks --> LLM --> Answer
\end{verbatim}

Limitations:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{No multi-hop:} Cannot answer ``What companies use technology X that competitor Y also uses?'' --- requires joining information across chunks.
  \item \textbf{No completeness guarantee:} Returns ``most relevant'' chunks, may miss critical information.
  \item \textbf{No structured reasoning:} Cannot traverse relationships.
  \item \textbf{Atomicity:} A single chunk may contain multiple facts, making attribution difficult.
\end{enumerate}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{GraphRAG Architecture}\label{sec:graphrag-arch}

The GraphRAG pipeline augments (or replaces) vector retrieval with KG traversal:

\begin{verbatim}
Query
  |
  v
Entity Linking (text --> KG entities)
  |
  v
Graph Traversal (BFS/DFS over KG paths)
  |
  v
Subgraph Extraction (paths or neighbourhood)
  |
  v
LLM Prompting (question + subgraph context)
  |
  v
Answer
\end{verbatim}

\begin{example}[Multi-hop GraphRAG]
Q: ``Who is the CEO of the company that acquired GitHub?''
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Entity link: ``GitHub'' $\to$ \texttt{github\_entity}
  \item Traverse \texttt{ACQUIRED\_BY}: \texttt{github\_entity} $\to$ \texttt{Microsoft}
  \item Traverse \texttt{CEO\_IS}: \texttt{Microsoft} $\to$ \texttt{Satya\_Nadella}
  \item Prompt: ``Based on the KG: [GitHub] --acquired\_by-- [Microsoft] --ceo\_is-- [Satya Nadella]. Answer: Satya Nadella''
\end{enumerate}
\end{example}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{GraphRAG Systems}\label{sec:graphrag-systems}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{GraphRAG systems compared}
\label{tab:graphrag-systems}
\begin{tabular}{lp{5cm}p{5cm}c}
\toprule
System & Key idea & KG construction & Year \\
\midrule
Microsoft GraphRAG & Community detection + LLM summarisation & LLM-based & 2024 \\
LightRAG & Dual-level (entity + relation) retrieval & LLM-based & 2024 \\
HippoRAG & PPR over KG + vector store hybrid & NLP pipeline & 2024 \\
HippoRAG 2 & Improved LLM-based KG construction & LLM-based & 2025 \\
GNN-RAG & GNN relevance scoring + path retrieval & From KGQA dataset & 2025 \\
GFM-RAG & Graph Foundation Model for RAG & Pretrained & 2025 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

\subsection{Microsoft GraphRAG in Detail}

\begin{enumerate}
  \item \textbf{Extract:} LLM extracts entities + relationships from each document chunk.
  \item \textbf{Detect communities:} Leiden algorithm finds hierarchical communities in the extracted KG.
  \item \textbf{Summarise:} LLM generates a summary for each community at each hierarchy level.
  \item \textbf{Query:}
    \begin{itemize}
      \item \textit{Local search:} Find relevant entities, traverse neighbours, retrieve community summaries.
      \item \textit{Global search:} Retrieve high-level community summaries that cover the entire corpus.
    \end{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Answer:} LLM synthesises retrieved information into a final answer.
\end{enumerate}

Key advance over standard RAG: answers requiring global understanding (``What are the main themes of this corpus?'').

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{KG-Augmented Generation: Beyond Retrieval}\label{sec:kg-constrained}

GraphRAG retrieves KG facts as context. A more powerful integration \emph{constrains} the LLM's generation to follow KG-valid paths.

\subsection{Graph-Constrained Reasoning (GCR)}

\begin{definition}[GCR (Luo et al., 2025)]
GCR builds a static trie over all KG paths reachable from a source entity. During generation, it masks logits so the LLM can only produce tokens forming valid KG paths. This guarantees 100\% structural faithfulness.
\end{definition}

\begin{verbatim}
           Entity Trie (partial)
                root
               /    \
          starred_in  produced_by
            /              \
        Blue_Hawaii     ...
       /          \
  directed_by   release_year
      /              \
  Michael_Moore     1961
\end{verbatim}

\subsection{Dynamic Oracle-Guided Decoding (DoG)}

DoG (Li et al., 2025) addresses GCR's limitation: GCR must enumerate all paths up front (exponential). DoG expands the trie \emph{dynamically}, adding child entities only after the parent is committed.

\subsection{DCA-Trie: Ontology-Aware Constrained Decoding}

DCA-Trie extends GCR with \emph{type oracle gates}: before expanding a relation from an entity, check whether the relation's range matches the expected type (from the KG ontology). This prunes semantically irrelevant paths without reducing path recall.

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Entity Linking for GraphRAG}\label{sec:el-graphrag}

\begin{table}[h]
\centering
\caption{Entity linking tools for GraphRAG}
\label{tab:el-tools}
\begin{tabular}{lp{5cm}p{4cm}}
\toprule
Tool & Approach & Licence \\
\midrule
REL (Radford et al.) & Neural ED with candidate generation & MIT \\
GENRE (De Cao et al.) & Autoregressive entity retrieval & MIT \\
Wikidata API & Direct search & Free \\
BLINK & BERT-based biencoder + cross-encoder & MIT \\
LLM-based & Prompt-based identification & N/A \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

% ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Exercises}

\begin{exercise}
Implement a minimal GraphRAG pipeline: given a query, link entities to Wikidata (via API), traverse 2 hops, and prompt an LLM with the retrieved subgraph.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
Compare standard RAG vs.\ GraphRAG on a multi-hop question (e.g., ``What is the capital of the country where the Eiffel Tower is located?''). Explain why standard RAG fails.
\end{exercise}

\begin{exercise}
Explain the GCR trie construction algorithm. What is its time complexity? How does DoG reduce this complexity? Under what conditions does DCA-Trie reduce the trie size without losing valid paths?
\end{exercise}


